description:
They are named for their beautiful bright intricate vein patterns on their leaves. Unlike most orchids, Jewel Orchids are more well known for their leaves rather than their flowers. Flowers are also rare to witness due to specific conditions during certain seasons to make it bloom. The flowers of this orchid species have obvious "filaments" which makes it very unusual compared to other orchid groups. There are also tiny hairs on the petals. The largest leaf is almost 50 mm while the whole plant is around 120 mm tall. Only grow low in the montane rainforest floor where it is dark and cool. It is related to Macodes spp. which are also known as Jewel Orchids.

ID thanks to Patrick Sodusta.

description:
Calanthe beamanii is an orchid species native to Sabah and Sarawak in Borneo, thriving in hill and lower montane forests at elevations between 700 to 1600 meters. This medium-sized terrestrial orchid features deep green leaves and elegant light purple or white flowers, blooming from spring through summer on erect flower stems. It requires warm, humid conditions and well-draining, organic-rich soil for optimal growth.

比埃曼蝦脊蘭是一種原產於婆羅洲沙巴和砂拉越的蘭花，生長於海拔700至1600米的山丘和低山森林中。這種中型地生蘭花具有深綠色的葉子和優雅的淺紫色或白色花朵，通常在春季至夏季期間開花，花莖直立。它需要溫暖潮濕的環境和排水良好、富含有機質的土壤以促進最佳生長。

description: First visit to this population in 2016.  Most blooming plants observed on this trip.

There is much confusion between Paphiopedilum volonteanum (imaged here) and Paphiopedilum hookerae.  Paph hookerae is a separate species of strictly western Borneo.  Paph volonteanum, is an ultramafic obligate of eastern Borneo.  These plants imaged within the Mesilau region of Kinabalu National Park.  

The nomenclature presented here is incorrect and there is no var. volonteanum.  Paph volonteanum and Paph hookerae are both full species located 1100 km apart.  See Orchid Digest, Sept-Oct 1981, pp 165-173  for the accurate description for these two species.
